sec.p:
Considering next external owners with high share ownership, we expect a negative relationship between preferred extent of disclosure and ownership. This is because at higher levels of ownership, external owners may acquire enough influence and power to pursue direct benefits meaningfully from the firm. If so, external owners with higher levels of ownership can be expected to seek reduced disclosure in order to shield their direct consumption from scrutiny.Figure 1b
                  depicts the countervailing effects of disclosure on direct ownership benefits (DB, direct benefits line) and share value ownership benefits (SB, share benefits line). When external owners have high holdings, SB starts at a higher level and is expected to rise sharply with increase in disclosure, reflecting the benefits to external owners of higher share prices on their substantial holdings from greater disclosure. With their high level of ownership, external owners may be able to draw substantial DB benefits as well. However, these direct benefits are vulnerable to disclosure since external owners are not as embedded as internal owners and because other external owners, who may rightfully make competing claims, may want these benefits eliminated if they cannot share them.6Thus, positing a sharp drop in the DB line, an increase in disclosure is expected to produce a greater marginal decrease in direct benefits than the gain in benefits from improved share prices. That is, total benefits (
                     \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $\mathrm{SB}\,+\mathrm{DB}\,$ \end{document}
                  ) decrease with increases in disclosure. Thus, if ownership is increased, external owners with high share ownership can be expected to seek decreases in disclosure.

fn.p:
Consider, e.g., two different situations. In case one, block holders own 60% of all shares, and the remaining 40% is held by dispersed individual investors. In the second case, block holders own 6% of all shares, and the remaining 94% is held by dispersed individual investors. Clearly, the block holders have greater relative power when they own a 60% block (the ownership is more concentrated). Measuring concentration of ownership using HF (see sec. III.1.B for calculation details) and assuming that each dispersed individual investor owns a negligible percentage of shares, HF is 0.36 in case 1 and 0.036 in case 2. Note also that splitting the blocks between two different block owners (e.g., 60% is split into two 30% blocks), gives an HF of
                           \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $[ ( 0.3) ^{2}+( 0.3) ^{2}] $ \end{document}
                        or 0.18. As higher values of HF indicate higher levels of concentration of ownership, these results are consistent with the intuition that block holders have less power than if there were a single 60% block.

sec.p:
An important issue concerning the construction of the disclosure index is the problem of how broad an index to construct, especially when there are problems in distinguishing “not disclosed” from “not applicable” items. We constructed three different indexes in order to test the sensitivity of the results to this potential problem. The first disclosure index includes only those items that were expected to apply to most companies; we refer to this as the “narrow” index. Two other indexes that include the items from the narrow index, as well as items that may be more subject to the “not applicable” problem were also constructed. We refer to these as the “somewhat broader” and the “comprehensive” indexes. Operationally, the disclosure index for a firm is defined as (
                     \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $\mathrm{number}\,\,\mathrm{of}\,\,\mathrm{items}\,\,\mathrm{disclosed}\,) / ( \mathrm{number}\,\,\mathrm{of}\,\,\mathrm{items}\,\,\mathrm{disclosed}\,+\mathrm{number}\,\,\mathrm{of}\,\,\mathrm{items}\,\,\mathrm{not}\,\,\mathrm{disclosed}\,$ \end{document}
                  ). Clearly, “not applicable” items are omitted from the calculation. The value of the disclosure index can range from zero to one. Higher values of the index indicate greater extent of disclosure.
